Q8: What kinds of deep-sea corals you are seeing in the Gulf of Mexico?
A8: It's tough to pick a few, but we are seeing many deep-sea corals & sponges. For example black coral (photo1) & sponges like this ping pong tree sponge (photo2)
#DeepSeaTV17 https://t.co/0CWvpBLSRi

Q7: What’s the largest creature you could expect to see at this sort of depth?
A7: Sperm whales can dive this deep! But in terms of invertebrates, some whip corals that have been seen on this expedition are up to 10 feet tall (photo).
#DeepSeaTV17 https://t.co/W7XV6yLAAN

Q6: How does the lighting from the Seirios ROV impact the behavior of the wildlife observed?
A6: Corals are great to study because they can’t move! Some fish will scatter, but squat lobsters are attracted to the light. More on lobsters here:
https://t.co/Rv9LKHQ2a0 #DeepSeaTV17
A5: Fungi were recently discovered in the deep-sea & in hydrothermal vents.There are few studies & we are still learning about the diversity of these organisms in the ocean. #DeepSeaTV17
Q5: Is there much research being done on deep sea fungi? Do they survive in depths where light does not penetrate? #DeepSeaTV17

Q4: How old are some of the deep-sea corals you are seeing in the Gulf of Mexico?

A4: The oldest aged corals are black coral which have been aged to about 2,000 years old. Several bamboo corals have been aged to ~100-500 years. #DeepSeaTV17
This is the first example of a yellow coral seen on the current dive in the #GulfofMexico. It's called Acanthogorgia @oceanexplorer #DeepSeaTV17 https://t.co/xl91hzdWZc

Q2: Why is it called a bamboo coral?

A2: These corals look like bamboo because they have alternating white calcium carbonate and darker, protein-rich segments, as you can see in this photo!
